- VSCode Version: Latest as of 12/4/16
- OS Version: 10.11.6 El Capitan

Is there any other setting necessary to have basic Javascript syntax checking/linting active in VSC? 

```
{
  "javascript.format.enable": true
}
```

ESLint works well when I `eslint --init` in a project but when I'm just fooling around with a few files and not building a project, it'd be great to just get basic syntax checking / undefined variable calls etc.  I was certain this was built into VSC.  And if it isn't, what exactly is  "javascript.format.enable" doing, because it doesn't seem to have any effect?

I also created a `jsconfig.json` in the folder root, but still no intellisense/lint happening:

```
{
    "compilerOptions": {
        "target": "ES6"
    },
    "exclude": [
        "node_modules"
    ],
    "files": [
        "src/"
    ]
}
```

Thanks!

- VSCode Version: 1.8.0 insiders
- OS Version: macOS Sierra

Steps to Reproduce:

Put the following in your settings.json file:

```

    "herp": [
        {
            "derp": {

            }
        }
    ],

    "editor.renderWhitespace": "all"
```

Notice how `editor.renderWhitespace` no longer shows the dropdown decorator that it normally would. This only happens if `editor.renderWhitespace` is _after_ the doubly nested object. If it precedes it, all is fine.

- VSCode Version: 1.7.2
- OS Version: Win7 x64

I have the following basic object:

```
// test.js
module.exports = {
  hello: 'world',
  callback: () => {
    console.log('test!');
  }
}
```

Using Node.js normally I can easily require this object and utilize it:

```
const test = require('./test');
console.log(test);
```
As expected, yields:
```
{ hello: 'world', callback: [Function: callback] }
```

However, when I am developing a VSCode extension, if I require this same exact file:
```
const vscode = require('vscode');
const test = require('./test');

let activate = (context) => {
  let disposable = vscode.commands.registerCommand('myExtension.myCommand', () => {
    console.log(test);
  });
  context.subscriptions.push(disposable);
}
exports.activate = activate;
let deactivate = () => { }
exports.deactivate = deactivate;
```
I get this:
```
{ hello: "world" }
```

The function that I specified in the exported object is completely ignored when it's required into the extension. I've never come across this with normal Node.js development. Can anyone shed some light on this? Is there something obvious I'm doing wrong that I'm just missing?
